When is the sound the loudest?: At night
Please describe the sound: Very low frequency Diesel engine like throbbing sound. Sometimes it drones on for long stretches before it has a short pause / throb, then picks up again, repeating the rhythm. Sometimes the droning / throb rhythm speeds up slightly and other times it has irregular quick throbs, similar to irregular heart beats. Can't block it out even when plugging ears; therefore it appears to be sensed by the body, which interprets it as sound. Only hear it / sense it inside enclosures; in house, parked car in driveway and partially outdoors when under carport, which has ceiling but open on 2 sides. Worse between 10 pm and 7am when all other external noises (e.g. traffic) are not or less present. Wakes me up middle of night when loudest between 2am and 3:30am and it's difficult to get back to sleep, if at all. Have heard it at other places I have visited. Within my very close group of family / acquaintances, which are about 13 people, only 3 can hear / sense it and 1 can only sense it.
Does the sound ever stop? Please tell us about this.: During full moon phases it seems to be quieter in the early hours of the evening, but still loud in the middle of the night. When it rains it seems to be less intense or not present. Just started hearing it in late August 2012, shortly after a drought and very hot temperatures in my area, so not sure if it is more prevalent during colder months until I get through a full year's cycle.
Does the sound ever "pulse" or "throb"?: Varies a lot
Where is it the loudest?: In house main floor
Have you tried tracking down the source of the noise?: With great effort
When did you start hearing it?: 2012
Can you provide a precise date when you first noticed it? (If "No", then leave blank): 2012-08-16
In which ear is it the strongest?: Left ear
Does your home have a "smart meter"?: Yes
Please list any unusual geographic, geological, or other features in your area: I am located in the Niagara escarpment area, which is vey hilly, very gravelly / sandy and there are lots of underground and above ground rivers / creeks. I am in Caledon Village, Ontario, Canada' which is 485 meteres above sea level. My ears pop every day due to elevation changes when going to / from work ( just kike in airplanes). There are multiple gravel pits within 1 - 5 miles, which have created mini lakes due to gravel / sand extraction. I am about 30 miles away (south / east) from windmills in Melanchthon, Ontario, Canada. There are no new cell towers. I am in a small subdivision surrounded by rural / farming and a green belt. We are on septic tanks and are on town water. Have gas (stove, fireplace, pool heater, dryer). Some neighbours are still on well water.

Sometimes these different sounds can start up abruptly, go on for days at intolerable sound levels, and stop abruptly, only to start up again within a very short time period. Weather definitely plays a part, and different phases of the moon or tides. Aproximately 4 days before a full or new moon, the sounds and vibrations become louder, during it and about 2 days after. LINK: http://web.archive.org/web/20080210150049/http://www.physics.otago.ac.nz/space/AARDDVARK_homepage.htm The Antarctic-Arctic Radiation-belt (Dynamic) Deposition - VLF Atmospheric Research Konsortium (AARDDVARK) provides continuous long-range observations of the lower-ionosphere. The Konsortia sensors detect changes in ionisation levels from ~30-85 km altitude, with the goal of increasing the understanding of energy coupling between the Earth's atmosphere, Sun, and Space. We use the upper atmosphere as a gigantic energetic particle detector to observe and understand changing energy flows; this Science area impacts our knowledge of global change, communications, and navigation. The joint NZ-UK Antarctic-Arctic Radiation-belt (Dynamic) Deposition - VLF Atmospheric Research Konsortia (AARDDVARK) is a new extension of a well-establish experimental technique, allowing long-range probing of ionisation changes at comparatively low altitudes. Most other instruments which can probe the same altitudes are limited to essentially overhead measurements. At this stage AARDDVARK is essentially unique, as similar systems are only deployed at a regional level.

Did we forget to ask anything? Do you have any other information or details for the project?: I believe this HUM is government related. They are using Extremely Low Frequency (ELF) for experiments and communication. ELF radio waves are generated by lightning and natural disturbances in Earth's magnetic field, so they are a subject of research by atmospheric scientists. Because of the difficulty of building transmitters that can generate such long waves, ELF frequencies have been used in only a very few manmade communication systems. ELF waves can penetrate seawater to a depth of several hundred feet, so the US and Russian military have used ELF transmission facilities to communicate with their submerged submarines. The frequency of alternating current flowing in electric power grids, 50 or 60 Hz, falls within this frequency band, and power grids are an unintentional source of ELF radiation. HAARP is a scientific endeavor aimed at studying the properties and behavior of the ionosphere, with particular emphasis on being able to understand and use it to enhance communications and surveillance systems for both civilian and defense purposes.

Timestamp[1]: Feb 5, 2013
When is the sound the loudest?: At night
Please describe the sound: A low droning hum--obviously--that persists most in my right ear. What I mean by this is that I can sometimes hear it in both ears, but I always hear it in my right ear when it happens, without fail. I don't recall ever hearing it throughout the day, it only seems to begin at night, often as I'm trying to fall asleep. I usually start to notice it after lying in bed for a few minutes. It's quite annoying. Not painful, but it certainly does like to keep me awake. Now, I have slight tinnitus too, but I've long since gotten used to that, as I've had it for as long as I can remember. I learned to almost completely ignore that a while ago. This 'humming' is very different from the tinnitus 'whining' or 'ringing'. I've been able to shut the tinnitus noises out by concentrating very hard on something, like creating a story in my mind, or working on a drawing. Doing challenging homework works, too. However, very rarely have my tried-and-true tactics worked to shut out the hum. It's not really that loud, it's just so constant and persistent and unusual that it really gets to me. I'd really like to have an explanation for it, but I understand that a true cause hasn't been found yet.
Does the sound ever stop? Please tell us about this.: The sound seems to persist until I fall asleep. I usually feel myself drifting off to sleep around 11:30 or 12:00 every night. Sometimes later, sometimes earlier. Later, around 1:00 or 3:00 in the morning, I usually wake up again for a few minutes to about a half hour. I don't know why, I just do. Sometimes I still hear the Hum then, other times I don't. I'd say it's about 50-50. By the time my alarm wakes me up again at 5:40, I don't hear the Hum anymore.

Did we forget to ask anything? Do you have any other information or details for the project?: I myself haven't heard the Hum in Nova Scotia. I put that entry in because my parents went on vacation to Nova Scotia I while ago, and upon learning about the Hum online just last year, I realized it matched the weird accounts they gave me about their time there. Apparently, they were on vacation somewhere in Nova Scotia--they aren't here right now for me to get confirmation on where exactly in NS they were--and they stayed at this cottage near the beach. They could hear a strange low droning hum in the area surrounding the cottage, if they concentrated hard on it, and they could hear it in the cottage itself more easily. Apparently, it was strongest in the bathroom. Upon entering the bathroom, both my parents report feeling a powerful force seeming to pull them down towards the floor, almost magnetically, as they described it, and they felt dizzy, too. Coupled with the strange force was a much louder Hum that seemed to begin beneath them and then rise up from the floor until the noise was all around them. The most curious thing about this scenario, in my opinion, is how the Hum's increase in volume seemed to tie in to the powerful pull towards the floor. It was so unusually strong that my mom was frightened by it, and refused to use the toilet or take a shower in that bathroom. (She visited a nearby friend's house to do so.) My dad was more stoic about it. They said that they'd like to go back there someday to experience it again, just because it was so unnatural. I'd like to go there too, because it sounds so utterly incredible. That's about all I have on the Hum. I hope my information can be helpful.

When is the sound the loudest?: At night
Please describe the sound: The hum as it starts sounds like some sort of large machine that is radiating sound. It gets louder then quieter, then louder and then quieter and continues the same pattern for a while before changing. The best analogy I can think of, is when another person has a ball on a string and is spinning it around really fast.When the ball is close to you, it sounds louder and when it further away it's a softer sound as it travels through the air. It is slow at first and begins to get louder over time. Also, the sound is very deep, like a bass in a stereo. It's not sharp, but instead a very soft pulsating hum. After the initial radiating hum pattern, it gets much louder and faster. It stays the same pitch however. Eventually, It sounds like a truck parked outside idling it's engine. But the location of the sound is impossible to find. Louder in some rooms than in others, and I can't help but feel the sound is coming from 'up' or in the air. When I open windows it does seem like the sound is coming from outside, but when I go out there, I literally have no idea where it could be located.
Does the sound ever stop? Please tell us about this.: Yes, the sound does stop. It always seems to last for around 10 minutes and continues to linger for a while thereafter. The initial 10 minute period is where the sound, to me, is unbearable. The sound kind of 'ramps down' in a steady decline until it is barely audible and then vanishes altogether. The entire process seems to take around a total of 15-20 minutes. Always at night, never during the day.

Did we forget to ask anything? Do you have any other information or details for the project?: I do want to add that if you have heard the noise, there will be no doubt in your mind. For me, it is unlike anything I've ever heard and it upsets my body on a physical level. Incredibly bizarre. If anyone is not sure if they have heard the hum, then they probably haven't. It is unmistakable. --I lived out in a small town, this is where I first heard the 'hum' about two years ago. It was about 3:00am when I heard it ( I remember because I checked the microwave for the time). It woke me from a dead sleep. I opened my window and looked outside, and saw nothing. The noise was SO loud. I went downstairs and searched the whole house because the sound was very irritating. I even went outside in the dead of night ( which I am very afraid to do because we are surrounded my woods and I am a total wuss.) I saw absolutely nothing. I felt like the sound was coming from 'up' but I could not pinpoint it. It was also a Full moon that night. I went back inside and paced my bedroom because I felt very annoyed and couldn't get back to sleep. The noise eventually faded and I went back to sleep. The whole episode lasted around 15 minutes. Portland ME, 04101- I now live in a city and while living here for 2 years I have been woken by the 'hum' four times. The most recent was actually last night at about 2:10am 2/12/2012. For me, there is always a 10 minute period of time where the sound is unbearable. I feel like it literally drives me nuts. Like nails scratching on a chalkboard. When I woke, I felt very hot just like previous occurrences. I also felt kind of sick in my stomach and had an adrenalin going--my heart was pumping pretty fast even though I was trying to breathe slowly. I felt so unbearably agitated. I really feel like something is being affected inside of me, it's a difficult feeling to describe, but I can feel this hum in my whole body. Every time this happens, I absolutely hate it. When the sound begins to fade, I start to feel better. And when it's gone completely, I feel suddenly very tired. I thought I was crazy until my boyfriend also heard the sound. Both him and I woke in the middle of the night to hear that strange 'humming' sound. He was as upset as I, and he ran around the apartment checking appliances and electronics to no avail. The sound was loudest in our bedroom and quieter in other rooms. I felt somewhat validated in the fact that he was able to hear it too. He even tried earplugs--which did not work. This lasted for about 10 minutes and then faded.

Timestamp[1]: Feb 28, 2013
When is the sound the loudest?: At night
Please describe the sound: The sound occurs between 2:00 am and 3:00 am usually in the first few weeks of winter, and early spring. I have actually noticed it for the past 10 years of living here. I have investigated it before, but never thought to do research online about it. The sound seems to be that of a low flying plane, moving at a very slow speed. It tends to go on for up to 15 minutes, then fade out. The fact that it lasts so long has lead me to believe that that its something other than your average aircraft. I have also noticed that when the sound is occurring, it does not sound as prominent outside, as it does inside of a structure. From my current location I have an unobstructed view of of the horizon in all directions except north. I can see the surrounding cities quite well, Pomona, La Verne, San Dimas. I might also mention that the sound becomes so intense sometimes that it drowns out the sound of the light freeway traffic occurring so early in the morning. "I do live blocks away from the 210 freeway." The sound 100% has nothing to do with the freeway, because I have been near the freeway to investigate and it was coming from traffic, it was coming seemingly from above. After becoming convinced that it was not my imagination, I gathered some willing friends to stay up with me to see if they were able to hear it. And sure enough, so far, I've shared the experience with over 20 people. We have stood outside, to see nothing. We've also noticed that it tends to happen only on clear nights. And going back to the freeway investigation, as soon as the sound stops, the sound of the traffic will become audible again from my current location. The frequency of the sound is so low and constant that it also can create the feeling of a rumbling sensation. Again, I have quite a bit to say about this "hum" and am quite happy to find a group of others who are experiencing the same or similar situations.
Does the sound ever stop? Please tell us about this.: Yes, the sound tends to stop after about 15 to 20 minutes. Then, usually after about half an hour, it returns for the same amount of time. This also lead me to believe that it was an aircraft, but there's zero evidence of one.
Does the sound ever "pulse" or "throb"?: Steady tone/hum

Please list any unusual geographic, geological, or other features in your area: As I mentioned, I have a very good view of the surrounding cities. Claremont is at the foot of the Mount San Antonio mountain range, and all of the surrounding cities are lower in elevation. Directly to the north of the city lies Mt. Baldy, Ontario and Cucamonga Peak. On top of a smaller mountain called "Sunset Peak" there are a series of radio towers which I have visited, but other than that there is nothing unusual about the area. Perhaps the mountain range is reflecting frequencies from much farther away, perhaps from machinery? I don't know really. I am currently in school for a degree in Electronic and Radio Communications, and don't see how "as some have mentioned" the sound could be coming from transmission towers or high-voltage lines.

When is the sound the loudest?: Same day and night
Please describe the sound: It started in the fall of 2010. I woke up around 9 a.m. one Saturday morning and I thought to myself "What the (bleep) is this now?" It sounded like a car idling outside my window. I waited for it to go away. It didn't, (and it hasn't, it is now Spring of 2013). I called the police late one night, about midnight, in the Winter of early 2011. The officer that came to my home couldn't hear it. My 14 year old son can't hear it. I unplugged ALL of my appliances and the hum was still there. I had my Sinuses surgically "drained" by an ENT at an outpatient surgery center in November of 2011 for other medical reasons. This did not relieve the hum. In the summer of 2012 a high pitched chirping sound like birds arguing or squirrels fighting started to accompany the hum sometimes. Now this sound is with the hum all the time after sunset. I'm not sure, but I think my dog can hear the hum. When the hum seems to be really intense the dog seems anxious and barks when there seems to be no reason (like visitors at the door). I made some telephone calls to find out if neighbors were running ceiling fans 24/7 (I live in a townhome) and the answer was no. I called the city offices and made inquiries, but they were not "aware" so of course I didn't press it. I drove around trying to find the source the summer of 2012. I found two possible sources. Large generators at the Minnesota Zoo and a dysfunctional restroom venting system at the Lebanon Hills Park off of Pilot Knob Road. I made inquiries about the nearby Quarry, asking if they are mining 24/7/365 and no one could tell me. I asked my neighbor if she could hear it one evening in the Summer of 2012 and she just pointed toward the St. Paul airport and said "It's the planes." She is 40 years of age and lives with an Air Force Veteran who is 50 year of age. It's NOT the planes. I know this hum is not tinnitus in my ears because when I close my ears (press the ear nub tight into my ears) I can not hear it anymore. I have some high pitched ringing tinnitus and when I close my ears and I can still hear that. In September of 2012, I became extremely ill. I was sick with nausea and diarrhea. While I was having the gastrointestinal trouble, I felt as if there was a huge pressure inside my head. It was a painless pressure that overcame everything. I told my son to call a friend, and she took me to the Hospital. At the Hospital I was placed on potassium and Antibiotics but there was no definitive diagnosis as to what made me sick, even after weeks of follow-up testing and a Colonoscopy in January of 2013. I feel a vibration in the floor of my home and in my furniture. At one point, while I was on the Antibiotics Cipro and Flagyl the Hum became intense and sounded like native war drums. After I completed the Antibiotics it returned to a low fluctuating hum. It goes where I go. I go to the Family Lake Home in Wisconsin and the hum is there. I go to different places and appointments in Mpls/StP and the hum is there. I have noticed that when I am standing near marble rock walls, (inside or outside) the hum is more intense. I do not hear it while I am driving or sitting in the car. It is louder inside my Garage than inside my home. I have an attached/tuck under garage.
Does the sound ever stop? Please tell us about this.: When it does seem to fade during the day, maybe once or twice a week in the afternoon, it returns within an hour. One night at around 3 a.m. in February of 2013 it was so loud and the vibration so strong the electrical outlets on my wall were 'rattling'. That has only happened once. I wake up some mornings wishing that it would stop.
Does the sound ever "pulse" or "throb"?: Around once per second on average

Approximately 1/2 hour before that earthquake occured, the oscillating hum sound that had been building the prior week or so switch over into an open, continuous 'claxon' sound for about 10 minutes. I as well (for the first time) this evening 1/1/13, upon arriving home heard the hum outside of my home in my driveway upon getting out of my car to enter my home. It was quite loud as well. Please describe the sound: Seldom one continuous hum. Always the feeling of this push and pull distant rumble. Often, at certain times, bursts of strong hum. At CET 08.00 hrs., 10.00 hrs., 11 hrs., 13.00 hrs.17.00 hrs.. It may continue on a medium level of unsettling loudness. During these periods it has been usual that it is actually the vibration that is completely upsetting the body and mind. Like probing the mind . The anguish, the brutal force of this recent type of hum is absolutely devastating. Late at night at 23.00 hrs. Often at 02.00 hrs. And early in the morning, almost every day, at 05.00 hrs. At this time the hum goes on till 08.00 hrs. From 08.00 hrs on the hum is strong, as stated before. When there is a continuous hum, it is usually strong, and it may continue for a few days.

When is the sound the loudest?:
Please describe the sound: What I hear each morning sounds like an industrial ventilation system, perhaps a (pulp mill) or white noise associated with airports where engines are tested....we have both these sources, they are at least 20km away. The noise is so steady, absolutely no harmonic fluctuation, consistant pitch, not a fossil fuel engine in my opinion. I have heard it at this location in Gibsons and north of Squamish b.c. very remote, no industry and thats when I wondered what was up, or was I suffering some sort of ear damage, I consider myself a musician and I am very sensitive to sound...especially disturbing sound. Please describe the sound: I consider this the same sound, coming from the same basic location - the train tracks. I live a few miles south of the train tracks now, and I sense the noise as coming from the same basic location. With my few miles of distance from Pocahontas Village Square, I sense the sound as slightly less acute, but still a very low frequency rumbling whine, churning and pulsating. I hear it upstairs on our second floor, and down in our concrete basement. I hear it some nights, after midnight. It usually subsides by morning, but some days, the sound continues into the day. I am usually not bothered by the sound, unless I am already having problems sleeping, stress, or anxiety. These instabilities seem to exacerbate my sensitivity to the sound, and the sound accentuates the instabilities. My cure is to remain positive, and to get plenty of exercise until my sleep patterns return to normal.

Timestamp[1]: Feb 3, 2013
When is the sound the loudest?:
Please describe the sound: The hum sounds like a low frequency rumble, as a qualified mechanic I would best describe it as an idle exhaust note from a car. The frequency is low, I would estimate somewhere around 50 hertz. There are subtle variations in volume and frequency, almost like a pulsing running through it although it's not regular or predictable. The median volume is very low and on occasion is inaudible, although the quiet periods tend to last for short periods (tens of minutes). Unfortunately the location is somewhat close to a motorway/freeway (approximately 700 meters away) which means during the day time the hum cannot be heard due to traffic noise. Most of my family can't hear it, however my daughter and my neighbour hear it as clearly as myself and often complain or comment about it.

When is the sound the loudest?:
Please describe the sound: A hum/drone/whine, apparently consisting of a combination of two constant pitches of slightly different qualities. The pitches are approximately in the middle octave of a piano a few tones apart. The vibration seems to penetrate inescapably and varies little from room to room. Oddly it seems to come from the direction where any window is in each room, regardless of orientation, hence my view that it is actually outside the property. The hum seems to come from outside the bungalow but is not audible outdoors due to the background sounds of nature such as air movement.

Timestamp[1]: Feb 10, 2013
When is the sound the loudest?:
Please describe the sound: Very low frequency hum, I would estimate the frequency between 50-120 htz. Sounds like a large Diesel engine generator or semi truck engine idling. Hum is not variable, stays at constant frequency, although at night while trying to sleep there is a slight increases in the intensity as if a load was put on an engine etc. When semi trucks are accelerating on a nearby road, I can hear the hum oscillating with the hum in the house. If everything in the house is quiet, I can move my head and notice the resonating hum in any room in the house including the basement. I do not hear the hum in some buildings in the downtown area of Peoria, IL, so I know it is an external sound not produced by my own ears.

Timestamp[1]: Feb 17, 2013
When is the sound the loudest?:
Please describe the sound: Intermittent pulsating/vibrating hum that occurs during the winter months when ground is frozen. The colder and more frozen the ground, the more intense and frequent. Sounds like an idling diesel train engine. I have eliminated all logical sources from my house and has been occuring for several years now. The noise makes the southwest corner of my house vibrate. This part of house sits on a concrete slab, no basement. Sound not heard outside. Basically, my wood framing and sheet rock acts like a speaker for this sound, which i thinks is coming from ground somewhere. Perhaps the frozen ground carries soundwaves better than soft ground is my theory.

When is the sound the loudest?:
Please describe the sound: Very deep rumbling Hum and vibration felt mostly on my chest, heart, gut, hands and feet. I feel those vibrations while lying on the bed, and my whole body trembles as if there is an earthquake. My muscles start twitching. My hubby also felt vibrations in the chest (while in the bed) although he is not a Hum hearer! The Hum is constant, with almost no breaks, and is getting louder after 10 pm. It becomes very aggressive when it is raining or the ground is wet/humid. I felt also my head vibrating with jaws and teeth while in a rested position in bed. It was quite strong and frightening. I also heard a banging sound from underneath (my mattress) and as if there was a gas ignition. The Hum can be so strong that I hear it outside on the balcony. I also feel very strong vibrations in the feet and pressure on the chest in the garden, while staying on the green grass.

When is the sound the loudest?: Same day and night
Please describe the sound: typical: engine idle type sound. also: steady hum with no pulse or buried pulse. pulse variations- slow, rapid, deep, steady, or slow broken asynchronous pulse. thunderous rumble, very light intensity to strong intensity. most often at night after 10:30pm for rumbles , but this can vary. heavy hum sounds like large, even huge industry. light hum sounds like small or distant industry. there is no industry here for at least 45 miles in any direction and then only isolated pockets of industry.
Does the sound ever stop? Please tell us about this.: not often , but yes sometimes. aug 30 - sept 4 , 2012 oct 10,2012. dec 14-15,2012 dec. 17-19, 2012 jan. 1-3,2013. quiet days throughout jan.2012. it would still rumble up late at night sometimes for only an hour or two. March and April.2013- the hum can go very light, almost imperceptible , yet still be detected. there were times in March & April when the hum would go obviously silent and then obviously come back strong. sometimes these transitions were very rapid , coming and going in perhaps ten minute intervals, more often the hum would appear briefly go away for an hour or two and then return again briefly. one morning it came and went at least 6 times. obviously on/obviously off. still very unusual hum behavior in my experience. often the hum will go lighter in the late afternoon or evening, and return stronger after 10:30pm CST. too many nights like these to keep track of. any patterns that the hum seems to follow it will then break. constantly innovating. the hum strikes me as a minimalist composer extraordinaire, except it's music is mostly awful.

Did we forget to ask anything? Do you have any other information or details for the project?: to the question: Where is it loudest ? I would have answered - all of the above. It is as loud inside as it is outside as it is 15 miles away. This seems to be a large hum area. A hum area location, as big as Windsor, Ontario. Canada. I have researched the Windsor Hum extensively and I keep track of current conditions there via a Facebook group. Often there are parallels or correlations. There is no industry where I live, yet often the hum I hear sounds like industry. I have heard Zug Island scale industry emanating from this hum. Hum super storms in Aug., Sept., Oct. , Nov. 2012. I would like to see a research brigade of hum hearers who could travel to different hum locations and corroborate these disparate hums. I believe the most sophisticated device for hum detection we have is hum hearers themselves. I would like to state that empirical study is science, and often is the best science. The map and the survey are a good example of this. Measurements would be great , but so far seem somehow problematic or inconclusive. The hum phenomenon has a history, an empirical history which should not be overlook or dismissed to easily. The salient characteristics of the hum for me are the description of what it sounds like and the description of the affect on the person. I believe this combination indicates "the hum", wherever or whenever.

Timestamp[1]: May 16, 2013
When is the sound the loudest?: Same day and night
Please describe the sound: Middle frequency hum. Only in quiet spaces. Any sound eliminates it. And when I move my head, even slightly it stops. If I continuously move my head it stops. For instance, if I make a series of figure 8's with my nose...as long as I'm moving the hum is gone. As soon as I stop moving it returns.
Does the sound ever stop? Please tell us about this.: It stops often. It will stop for months and then return for months. Sometimes it will stop for a week or two, sometimes a day or two. It's nice when it stops. Any sound will make it stop. Slight wind or the rustle of trees and grass outside will make it stop. There is usually enough ambient sound out of doors that I never hear it unless I'm indoors and it's quiet. And as I said above, head movement makes it stop. In answer to where is it the loudest below...it's the loudest in very quiet areas. Upstairs, downstairs, basement...location doesn't matter other than it must be a quiet location.

Do you have any medical issues with your hearing?: No medical issues with hearing. I was tested for tinnitus and oto-acoustic emissions at University of New Mexico during original hum investigation in 1990's
Did we forget to ask anything? Do you have any other information or details for the project?: I was a participant and part of the team that investigated the Taos Hum under Prof. Joe Mullins of the UNM Mechanical Engineering Dept. I spent several nights attempting to detect the hum with then Sandia National Lab tech Horace Poteet. Horace could also sense the hum and he and I verified it's presence so that other members of the team could attempt a detection using a variety of sensors. Horace and I used the "Big Ear" microphone developed by Prof. Joe Mullins and we attempted to capture the hum. We could not find any evidence of an acoustic low frequency sound signature and at one point early in the morning, looked at each other and declared "this is not a sound." The remainder of the team present held a short meeting at which one of them said he needed to brush up on his "Tesla." Although I am not listed as a team member, I can assure you that I was in fact present during the attempt to capture the hum and that the following day I presented the team with a perfect match for the hum by using two audio oscillators at 31 HZ with one of the audio oscillators de-tuned to produce a slow beat frequency. I then added a little bit of FM modulation to one of the tones and that was a match. I find that the survey questions do not go deep enough. For example, "Which ear is it the strongest?" Since I do not believe that I am "hearing" the hum, I am not using my ears as sensors. I chose the answer "not sure." There, perhaps, should be a category asking if the respondent senses or hears the hum. For me, after a long and thorough search for hums source, I have determined that it I sense it but do not hear it. Here is another bit of general observation. Once, I was ascending the Picuris Peak mountain in the winter during 1993 or 1994 and I had to wait while my partner attempted to break a trail to the peak. It was very, very quiet with freshly fallen snow and as I settled in to wait, the hum was easily discerned. I spent my time focusing on it, trying to determine a pattern to it's beat and modulation. I realized that it seemed to be "intelligently" varied as I could determine no random nature to it's pattern. It reminded me of a modem. A carrier with data encrypted as modulation. As I was making this "observation" the hum suddenly stopped! There were a few seconds of absolute silence and then I heard the approach of the Doppler of a high flying jet aircraft which effectively masked the hum. As the aircraft passed by and I could no longer hear it, again there was a few seconds of silence after which the hum returned. This was repeated a few times as more high flying jet aircraft passed by. I do not believe that the jet aircraft had anything to do with the cause of the hum as they were most likely scheduled passenger jet service. What I did determine from the observation is that although the sound of the jet aircraft effectively masked the hum, there were the few seconds of silence on either side of the audible masking. Perhaps I could sense the masking but not hear the jet aircraft as it just came into and just went out of my hearing range. I am interested in contributing more to this on-going mystery, although I have reason to believe that the Taos hum is associated with the US Navy ELF Submarine Communications system. I have also noted an increase in intensity of the hum during times of heightened military alert prior to the Iraq - Afghanistan wars. Now, there seems to be a permanent state of heightened military alert. I have also learned how to effectively block the hum from affecting me in my daily life. I only have to focus on sensing it to recall it now. I lived in Taos from 1972 until 2002 with only a few years spent in California and Colorado. I now live near Sarasota, Florida and on cool autumn and spring nights when everyone's AC is not running, the hum comes out of mask and into my senses.

I even heard it, but not so loud, when we went on holiday to Spain (again only at night). I can't hear it outside the house but it's all over the interior of the house. Another good description of the sound is like a car parked outside the house with the engine running. I believe when it was strong it affected my health and recently I had the most debilitating flu I have had for years.

Please describe the sound: It sounds like a large 18-wheeler hauling something big, like windmill or industrial plant parts on the highway about a half mile away, except the highway where i am is about two miles away and the sound itself never grows or diminishes like you could expect for something that approaches and then, logically, leaves in another direction. Just a large humming noise that last on average about 2-3 minutes. I usually hear it when I'm smoking outside so i've never really heard it 'start', just the last few minutes while i smoke. Another way to describe it is like distant thunder, except it goes on for minutes as opposed to short pulses.
Does the sound ever stop? Please tell us about this.: Yes, see above. I usually hear it for a few minutes on my smoke break. It doesn't really taper off, it's just then, and then there's a sharp decline and then it's gone. It's somewhat regular in that i'll catch it sometimes 2-3 times a night at different volume levels. Although I don't hear it every night.

When is the sound the loudest?:
Please describe the sound: I have heard two separate and distinct noises over time. One seems to match the description of the massive diesel engine in the distance. It was loud enough for me to consider calling the police to report it. I assumed there was a massive municipal project that needed to be accomplished at night, and tried to forget about it. I was alone at the time of the incident, and had nobody else in my proximity to verify the noise. It was more than loud enough to keep me awake. The second noise I have heard, a noise that was also heard by another 19 year old male friend of mine is more frequent. It is a higher pitch than the noise described above. It sounds like a very faint tornado siren(I understand this noise is different in many areas). We have heard this particular noise on many occasions. I can not confirm the weather in these situations, but on a gut instinct, I would say it was generally overcast with no rain. I have no specific memory of ever hearing this noise on a clear or rainy night. Noise 2: - various locations including but not limited to Hall Road and Utica Road Shelby Township, Michigan

Note that the hum doesn't actually continue during this secondary noise event... it actually pauses (like muting a TV) and resumes when the noise stops.

Timestamp[1]: Jun 24, 2013
When is the sound the loudest?: At night
Please describe the sound: I have heard industrial electrical transformers, or electrical motors make a similar noise. If you've ever heard the windings on a motor vibrate, usually if the motor is just starting to rotate, or is jammed stationary, this would be the closest analog I could use to describe it.
Does the sound ever stop? Please tell us about this.: I only notice it at night, or early in the morning, in my bedroom. The sound drops significantly as you move away from that corner of the house. I've investigated the PIG transformer on the pole next to my property, the drop and meter to my house (the electrical drop is right next to the bedroom window), the breaker panel, in my garage (below my bedroom), and my neighbor's AC condenser, which is on the side of her house next to mine, and my bedroom. None of these things produce any significant vibration in the air or the ground, or to the touch, that matches the hum. The neighbors AC condenser has been ruled out because the hum can be there without the condenser running. I've also eliminated my tinitus, as my fiancee hears it too, at the same time as I. I don't notice it during the day, ever. Windows open or closed has no effect. I haven't heard it outside, but I haven't investigated outside at night. I do notice a lot of distant vibration does effect my house, such as trucks or traffic from about 1/4 mile away, while lying in my bed. With one ear down on the bed and a window open, I can match vibration through the ground and sound from the distance. I've noticed it the year I moved into the house, winter, 2011. The house is a raised ranch built around 1976. The hum is omni directional when in the north west corner of the house. It fades drastically when you move away from there.
Does the sound ever "pulse" or "throb"?: Steady tone/hum
Where is it the loudest?: In house main floor
Have you tried tracking down the source of the noise?: With some effort
When did you start hearing it?: 2011

In which ear is it the strongest?: equally in both ears

Please describe the sound: Very loud hum resembling a B-52 flying overhead or a large cruise ship engine. The hum seems to come from a swath of space approximately 60 degrees in width, sometimes seemingly eminating from the mountains themselves, sometimes sounding like it is coming from the air directly above the mountains. At some points in time/locations the hum sounds like it is coming from all directions. The hum is always there, only this one particular spot in the mountains. I've visited the location around 10-15 times and have spent time from sun up to sundown there, always with the hum. The hum loudness will fluctuate slightly throughout the day, estimating something between 60% of volume to max of 100% volume. No matter how close I get to the apparant source I can never locate it. If I place earphones over my ears (with no sound coming from the earphones), the hum will deaden, or reduce in volume by approximately 50%. I'm fairly certain the vibration from the hum can be felt throughout my body.

The longer I listened, however, I noticed there was no beat or anyone around. The sound was very low, and the speed of it's "wub wub wub"s were varied and sporadic. It sounded almost mechanical, or electronic..
